This code is fairly simple:
```
int max = Integer.MIN_VALUE, sum = 0;
for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++){
    sum += nums[i];
    if(sum > max)
        max = sum;
    if(sum < 0)
        sum = 0;
}
return max;
```
The reasoning behind this is fairly straight forward. 
The first line of the loop is increasing our sum. 
The first `if-statement` is checking to see if it's the best we've found so far
The second `if-statement` is checking if the sum is less than 0. If it is, it's better to discard whatever we have so far, and start fresh from 0. A negative number + `x` will always be less than `x`. 

These can be shortened further if you wish to be like so:
```
int max = Integer.MIN_VALUE, sum = 0;
for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++){
    sum += nums[i];
    max = Math.max(sum, max);
    sum = Math.max(sum, 0);
}
return max;
```
Lastly, here's a java tip:
The return value of an assignment operation is the value that was assigned. This allows for some more shortening of the code to the following:
```
int max = Integer.MIN_VALUE, sum = 0;
for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++){
        max = Math.max(sum+=nums[i], max);
        sum = Math.max(sum, 0);
}
return max;
```
`sum += nums[i]` is usually a line all by itself, but because it's an assignment operation, it also has a return value that is equal to the value assigned. This allows you to both assign a value AND use the value immediately. 
For example:
`(i=1)==1` -> always true because `1 == 1`
`(sum = sum + nums[i]) > nums[i]` is true only if `sum` was non-negative beforehand. 
The += operation is shorthand for something like the line directly above where something is added to a variable and then stored back in that same variable.

