'''

	class Solution {
		public int findMin(int[] nums) {

		int start = 0;
        int end = nums.length -1;

            while (start <= end) {
                int mid = start + (end - start)/2;

                if (mid < end && nums[mid] > nums[mid + 1])
                    return nums[mid + 1];     // greater index holds the min element in the array
                if (start < mid && nums[mid - 1] > nums[mid] )
                    return nums[mid];     //  greater index holds the min element in the array

				if (nums[start] > nums[mid])    // search in the left half 
                    end = mid - 1;
                else    // search in the right half
                    start = mid + 1;
            } 
        return nums[0];
		}
	}
'''	
*Logic : Return nums[pivot + 1] or return nums[0] if array is sorted.*

Time complexity - O(logn)
Space complexity - O(1)


1. Apply Binary Search for best time complexity of O(logn).
2. Find and return nums[pivot + 1]
3. If no pivot exists, array is sorted, simply return the first element of the array.


What is this pivot?
It is the index where the existing element and the next element do not follow the order of the array, if its ascending then the element at pivot index and pivot + 1 index will be descending and vice versa.

It is usually the index of the largest element in asc rotated sorted array and index of the smallest number in desc rotated sorted array.
For example in
'''

		// rotated asc array
		arrary1 = {3, 4, 5, 1, 2} 
		// pivot index is 3 where the largest element lies.

		// rotated desc array
		array2 = {7, 6, 10, 9, 8}
		// pivot index is 1 where the smallest element lies.
'''
Consider a given array
'''

	int arr[] = {4,5,6,7,0,1,2}
	// here pivot is the 3rd index
	// the minimum element is next the pivot index i.e 4th index and element is 0 which is the minimum
	int arr2[] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
	// here we do not have a pivot, array is sorted just return the first element i.e. 1 which is the minimum.
'''

Now lets find the pivot and return the next element after the pivot index as this will be the minimum element in the array.

4 Cases to find pivot index

'''

	if nums[mid] > nums[mid +1]
		return nums[mid + 1]; // since nums[pivot + 1] is the minimum element in the array
	if nums[mid - 1] > nums[mid]
		return nums[mid];
	if nums[start] > nums[mid] // search in the left half
		end = mid - 1;
	else // search in the right half
		start = mid + 1;
'''

We can solve this question even in linear time, there is no harm in giving it a try.
Note ** Linear Search vs Binary Search-

**For every million comparisions in linear search there is only 19 comparisions in binary search in worst case senarios. Binary Search is very efficient specially with greater i/p size.**

'''

	public class Main{
		public int findMin(int[] nums) {

			for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
				if (nums[i] > nums[i+1]) {  // checking for flaws ie different order.
					return nums[i+1];     // min element lie after the max element
				}
			}
			return nums[0];     // if array is not rotated
		}
	}

'''

*Logic - Iterate through the array try to find an anomaly and return the i + 1 index which holds the min element in the array.*
Time Complexity - O(n)
Space Complexity - O(1)
