__*Please draw out sample test cases and dry run the program along these steps to get a better intuition*__

Here are a few sample cases for your convenience : 
*  Input : [3,4,5,1,2],  Output : 1
*  Input : [4,5,6,7,0,1,2] , Output : 0
*  Input : [11,13,15,17], Ouput : 11

*If you like this explanation, please upvote
Comment down below in case you have some suggestion/doubt*

__Approach :__

1. We will manage 2 pointers (index pointers) - __low__ and __high__
2. Initially low will point to 0 index of array, high will point to n-1 index of the array
3. while __low<=high__ we will calculate mid
4. If __nums[mid] is smaller than nums[high]__ it means that the lowest number cannot be in __[mid,high]__ and it must be in __[low,mid]__ therefore set __high = mid__
5. if __nums[mid]__ is greater than __nums[high]__ it means that the lowest number cannot be in __[low,mid]__ and must be in __[mid,high]__ therefore set __low = mid+1__
6. Finally, when __low>high__ the loop will break and we can guarantee that __high and mid__ will both be containing the index of the lowest element.
7. return __nums[mid]__

__Code :__
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findMin(vector<int>& nums) {
        int low = 0;
        int high = nums.size() - 1;
        int mid;
        while(low<=high){
            mid = (low+high) / 2;
            if(nums[mid]<nums[high]){
                high = mid;
            }
            else{
                low = mid+1;
            }
        }
        return nums[mid];
    }
};
```

__Complexity :__


Time : O(logn) [Modified binary search]
Space : O(1) [Only mid, low, high i.e. 3\*integer_size]

