solutions.content:
**Idea**

* We basically need to find the smallest element
We can do that by binary search as follows:
* Binary search, left (Starting) = 0, right (Last element) = n-1
* `mid = left + (right - left) / 2 // Or (Left + Right)/2` 
* If `nums[left] > nums[right]`, then `nums[left]` is the minimum (Basically, after completing the iteration or on not fullfillment of the condition, we will reach here. Else we continue traversing)
* Else, traverse
	* If `nums[mid] > nums[right]` then search on the right side, because smaller elements are in the right side
	* Else search on the left side.

**SOLUTION**
`In C++`
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findMin(vector<int>& nums) {
        int left = 0 , right = nums.size()-1 ;
        if (!right)  // Case of single element
            return nums[0] ;
        while (left < right)
        {
            int mid = left + (right - left) / 2;
            if (nums[left] < nums[right]) 
                return nums[left];  // Smaller element
            else if (nums[mid] > nums[right]) 
                left = mid + 1;  // Check on right
            else 
                right = mid; // Check on left
        }
        return nums[left];
    }
};
```
`In JAVA`
```
class Solution {
    public int findMin(int[] nums) {
        int left = 0;
        int right = nums.length - 1;

        while(left < right){
            int mid = left + (right - left) /2;

            if(nums[mid] > nums[right])
            {
                left = mid + 1;
            }
            else if(nums[mid] < nums[right])
            {
                right = mid;
            }
            else
            {
                return nums[right];
            }
        }
        return nums[left];
    }
}
```
