# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The given code aims to find the minimum element in a rotated sorted array.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- Check if the length of the array "nums" is 1. If true, return the single element as the minimum.
- Initialize two pointers: "left" pointing to the start of the array and "right" pointing to the end of the array.
- Check if the array is not rotated, i.e., the element at the leftmost index is less than the element at the rightmost index. If true, return the element at the leftmost index as the minimum.
- Enter a while loop while the "left" pointer is less than or equal to the "right" pointer.
- Inside the loop, check if the subarray between "left" and "right" has only two elements. If true, return the element at the "right" index as the minimum.
- Calculate the middle index "m" using binary search formula (left + (right - left) / 2).
- Compare the element at index "m" with the element at the "right" index.
1. If nums[m] > nums[right], it means the minimum element lies to the right of "m". Update the "left" pointer to "m".
2. Otherwise, the minimum element lies to the left of "m" or is equal to "m". Update the "right" pointer to "m".
- Repeat steps 6-7 until the minimum element is found.
- Finally, return the element at the "left" index as the minimum.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time complexity of this solution is O(log n) because it uses binary search to find the minimum element. The array is divided in half at each step, reducing the search space.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity is O(1) because the algorithm uses a constant amount of additional space to store the pointers and variables, regardless of the size of the input array.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int findMin(int[] nums) {
        if(nums.length==1)
            return nums[0];
        int left=0;
        int right=nums.length-1;
        //not rotated
        if(nums[left]<nums[right])
            return nums[left];
        while(left <= right)
        {
            if(right-left==1)
            {
                return nums[right];
            }
            int m = left + (right-left)/2;
            if(nums[m] > nums[right])
                left = m;
            else
                right = m;
        }
        return nums[left];
    }
}
```

